# Client routing

1. URL Structure: Feature/Role-based first, Resource-based second
Use semantic URLs starting with the feature or role and continuing with the relevant resource. Examples: /admin/templates, page/templates/:id, etc.
2. State Management: React Router Loaders & Actions
Use loaders to fetch data needed for routes before components render
Use actions to handle mutations (form submissions, state changes)
Access data via useLoaderData() in components
3. Transition Logic: Unified Loader Checks
All conditional navigation logic goes in route loaders
Create reusable check functions for common conditions
Components focus purely on rendering UI based on loader data
4. Authentication: Loader-Based Auth Checks
Verify authentication in route loaders before components render
Use redirects to send unauthorized users to login
Encapsulate auth checks in reusable functions
5. Nested Routing: Logical Feature Grouping
Group related routes by feature: /stories/*, /templates, /admin
Use shared layouts for route groups
Create index routes for feature landing pages
6. Route Naming: Kebab-Case and Resource-Focused
Use consistent kebab-case for URL paths
Focus on resources rather than actions: /templates vs /browse-templates
Keep URLs clear and concise
7. Code Organization: Feature-Based Routing
Define routes within feature folders (game/gameRoutes.tsx)
Compose the main router from these feature-specific route definitions
Keep routes close to their related components
8. Error Handling: Nested Error Boundaries
Define error boundaries at different levels of the route hierarchy
Handle specific errors contextually (e.g., template not found)
Use a global fallback for unhandled errors

